n's writings. This book collects for the first time, translates, and offers explanatory notes on all the substantial fragments of ancient philological and historical commentaries on Demosthenes. Using these texts to illuminate an important aspect of Graeco-Roman antiquity that has hitherto been difficult to glimpse, Gibson gives a detailed portrait of a scholarly industry that touched generations of ancient readers from the first century b.c. to the fifth century and beyond.In this lucidly organized work, Gibson surveys the physical form of the commentaries, traces the history of how they were passed down, and explains their sources, interests, and readership. He also includes a complete collection of Greek texts, English translations, and detailed notes on the commentaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aOratory, Ancient. 0aSpeeches, addresses, etc., GreekxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aancient greece.  aancient world.  aantiquity.  aargumentation.  aassembly.  aathens.  aclassical rhetoric.  aclassicism.  acontemporary audience.  ademosthenes.  adidymus.  afifth century.  afuneral oration.  agreece.  agreek texts.  aharpocration.  ahellenism.  ahistorical context.  aideal audience.  alaw.  alegal.  alinguistics.  alove.  anonfiction.  aoratory.  apersia.  aphilosophy.  apolitical philosophy.  apolitical science.  apolitician.  apolitics.  apublic speaking.  arhetcomp.  arhetoric.  aspartans.  aspeeches.  astatesman.  atrials.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022956340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092730840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927308423Coveruhttps://